      {
        "paragraph_index": 4,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insights\n\n- **Only two ammine complexes form**: Unlike Cu²⁺ or Ni²⁺ which form up to 4–6 ammine complexes, Ag⁺ (d¹⁰, linear coordination preference) stops at the diamine [Ag(NH₃)₂]⁺ — the classic linear two-coordinate complex responsible for dissolving AgCl in ammonia solution (Tollens' reagent).\n\n- **The spread in log β values** (e.g., log β₂ = 7.14–8.18) reflects genuine ionic-strength dependence: constants measured at high ionic strength (I up to 5 M) are systematically lower than those at infinite dilution (I → 0), consistent with activity coefficient effects on charged species.\n\n- **Negative ΔS for β₂** (−46 to −56 J/mol·K) indicates significant ordering of the coordination sphere and solvent upon binding two NH₃ ligands, even though the reaction is enthalpically driven (ΔH ≈ −59 kJ/mol).\n\n> All data from NIST SRD-46 (16 independent reference equilibrium networks, literature spanning multiple ionic media including KNO₃, NaNO₃, and NaClO₄).",
        "claims": [
          {
            "start": 0,
            "end": 22,
            "text": "### Chemistry Insights",
            "claim_type": "filler",
            "metadata": {
              "classifier_strategy_version": "react-v7-schema-salvage-markdown-anchor",
